          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the rheumatoid nodule described in the case, which cells form the characteristic palisading ring around the zone of fibrinoid necrosis?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fibroblasts</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Fibroblasts are the most common resident cells of loose connective tissue and synthesise collagen and ground substance, but they are found in the outermost zone of the nodule, not in the palisading ring.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Macrophages (histiocytes)</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Elongated macrophages (histiocytes) arrange radially around the central fibrinoid necrosis, forming the palisade — a diagnostic hallmark of the rheumatoid nodule.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Mast cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Mast cells are resident connective tissue cells packed with histamine granules that mediate allergic responses, but they do not form palisades in rheumatoid nodules.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Plasma cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Plasma cells are antibody-secreting B-lymphocyte derivatives found in the outermost zone of the nodule alongside lymphocytes, not in the palisading layer.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The palisading cells are macrophages (histiocytes). These resident immune cells of loose connective tissue accumulate and arrange radially when chronic inflammation from the adjacent joint triggers their activation."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The palisading arrangement of macrophages (histiocytes) around fibrinoid necrosis is the histological hallmark of a rheumatoid nodule, illustrating how resident immune cells of loose connective tissue reorganise during chronic inflammation."
                }
              ],
