          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During wound healing, fibroblasts differentiate into myofibroblasts. What is the</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During wound healing, fibroblasts differentiate into myofibroblasts. What is the primary functional advantage of this transformation?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Increased secretion of antibodies</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Antibody secretion is the function of plasma cells — terminally differentiated B lymphocytes with abundant rough endoplasmic reticulum and a prominent Golgi apparatus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Enhanced phagocytosis of cellular debris</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Phagocytosis is the primary function of macrophages, whose lysosomes fuse with phagosomes to destroy engulfed material. Myofibroblasts serve a different role in healing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Contraction of wound edges</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Myofibroblasts acquire actin filaments that generate contractile force, pulling wound edges together and reducing wound size during the repair process.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Degranulation of histamine stores</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Histamine degranulation is the function of mast cells, triggered when allergens bind to surface IgE receptors — an immune response unrelated to wound contraction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Myofibroblasts use actin filaments to contract wound edges — a unique function distinct from phagocytosis (macrophages), degranulation (mast cells), or antibody secretion (plasma cells)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. Actin filaments in myofibroblasts act as a contractile apparatus that closes wounds. When this process is overactive, excess collagen deposition leads to keloid scarring."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
